**Overall Meaning:**

"If it is said that the body is the characteristic of a Brahmin, that is not true either.  Because all humans, from the lowest outcaste to the highest, share the same five elements in their bodies.  We see the same old age, death, righteousness, unrighteousness, etc. in all humans.  There is no rule that a Brahmin should be white, Kshatriya red, Vaishya yellow, and Shudra black.  Furthermore, burning the body of a father, etc. leads to the sin of killing a Brahmin, etc. for the son, etc. Therefore, the body cannot define a Brahmin."

**Explanation:**

This verse dismisses the body as the defining factor of Brahminhood. It points out the commonality of human bodies across social classes, highlighting shared physical characteristics and experiences. It also rejects the notion of caste-based skin color as a valid identifier.  The verse further criticizes the ritualistic practice of cremation and its potential to lead to spiritual sin, ultimately concluding that the body cannot determine Brahminhood. 
